Syria today. But what are

17:09.829 --> 17:13.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the prospects of cooperating
with Russia to end the Syrian
conflict?

17:13.099 --> 17:16.068 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We get two views.

17:16.068 --> 17:21.674 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Evelyn Farkas was deputy
assistant secretary of defense
for Russia and Eurasia from 2012

17:21.674 --> 17:25.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to earlier this year. And Vali
Nasr is the dean of the School
of Advanced International

17:25.578 --> 17:29.015 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
Studies at Johns
Hopkins University.

17:29.015 --> 17:33.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Vali Nasr, let's talk about
timing. Why the stepped-up
action by Russia now?

17:33.853 --> 17:36.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VALI NASR, School of Advanced
International Studies, Johns
Hopkins University: Well, they

17:36.522 --> 17:41.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had the attack on their plane in
Sinai and the attack in Paris.
It actually gives them

17:41.694 --> 17:46.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an opportunity to argue that
ISIS should be the top priority
for the international community

17:46.699 --> 17:48.601 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Syria.

17:48.601 --> 17:53.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Putin has been arguing this all
along. He doesn't have many
people actually taking this

17:53.639 --> 17:58.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at face value. Now he sees an
opportunity, given what's
happened in Paris, to align
European

17:58.878 --> 18:03.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
positions with himself. So
he's stepping up pressure.

18:03.249 --> 18:08.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But Putin didn't
acknowledge until today that
there was even terrorism
involved

18:08.321 --> 18:12.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the shoot-down or whatever
happened to the Metrojet plane
over the Sinai. Is he to

18:12.358 --> 18:14.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
be trusted on this?

18:14.427 --> 18:19.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VALI NASR: Well, what we can see
is that Paris has been a
game-changer.

18:19.799 --> 18:25.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It has shifted the focus in
Europe and potentially the
United States on ISIS. This
actually gives

18:25.604 --> 18:30.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russia an opportunity to align
its Syria policy with that of
the West, so let's say to find

18:30.743 --> 18:33.045 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a common ground.

18:33.045 --> 18:37.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it makes sense for him, ahead
of meeting with President
Hollande, to say, we're both

18:37.316 --> 18:41.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
facing the same problem. This
happened to me in Sinai. This
has happened to you in Paris.

18:41.687 --> 18:44.690 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Let's coordinate and
cooperate on this.

18:44.690 --> 18:49.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, Evelyn Farkas,
we have common interests,
theoretically, and, therefore,

18:49.628 --> 18:52.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
strange bedfellows can get
together. Is this a brand-new
day when it comes to the
U.S.-Russia-France

18:52.331 --> 18:54.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
relationship?

18:54.233 --> 18:59.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS, Former Defense
Department Official: Sadly,
Gwen, I don't think so.

18:59.238 --> 19:03.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it is an opportunity for
the Russians to acknowledge that
we have a shared foe,

19:03.642 --> 19:08.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if we will, in ISIS, Da'esh,
ISIL, whatever you want to call
it. The Russians have been

19:08.748 --> 19:11.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
saying that rhetorically for
quite some time. In fact, they
have been talking about
combating

19:11.083 --> 19:14.320 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
terrorism with us for years now.

19:14.320 --> 19:18.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think the proof will
really be in what they hit and
not just tonight, but moving

19:18.057 --> 19:21.927 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
into the weeks and the
next couple of days.

19:21.927 --> 19:25.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: What should be the
United States be doing with
this, what feels not quite like

19:25.498 --> 19:28.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an olive branch but at least
a reach-out from Russia?

19:28.768 --> 19:32.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: I think we should
try. We should always try to
cooperate with Russia, but I'm

19:32.638 --> 19:37.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
skeptical, because essentially
our objectives in Syria and
actually beyond Syria are not

19:37.009 --> 19:39.278 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
aligned with Russia's

19:39.278 --> 19:43.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And until they're aligned, until
one side or other or both sides
can compromise, I think

19:43.916 --> 19:47.953 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there will be limits to any kind
of cooperation we can have with
Russia.

19:47.953 --> 19:51.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: In fact, Vali Nasr,
Vladimir Putin has accused the
U.S. in the past of playing

19:51.323 --> 19:54.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a double game when it comes to
the Middle East. What's changed?

19:54.960 --> 19:59.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VALI NASR: Well, nothing has
changed, in the sense that our
position, as Evelyn says, is

19:59.832 --> 20:03.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very different from Russia's,
not only in the Middle East, but
beyond.

20:03.702 --> 20:08.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there is a lot of pressure
now on European governments and
also on the U.S. government

20:08.841 --> 20:13.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to find a way to address the
ISIS problem. We're seeing the
receding of the importance

20:13.746 --> 20:18.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Assad in resolution of the --
the immediate resolution of the
Syria crisis and addressing

20:18.551 --> 20:23.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
U.S. and Europe's security
problems compared to ISIS.

20:23.756 --> 20:28.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in the military arena, we
have one set of problems
actually working with the
Russians,

20:28.627 --> 20:32.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in that we don't know what
they're hitting, what they will
do. But then there is the
diplomatic

20:32.531 --> 20:38.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
front in Vienna. And I think
Putin is counting on the fact
that the Europeans now feel
pressure

20:38.003 --> 20:41.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that this war has to end more
quickly or we should get to a
cease-fire.

20:41.974 --> 20:45.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is not going to happen by
insisting on Assad going. It
will happen by creating some

20:45.277 --> 20:47.680 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
common ground around ISIS.

20:47.680 --> 20:52.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Have we reached a
point where any road to peace or
at least road to cooperation

20:52.084 --> 20:54.220 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
has to run through Moscow?

20:54.220 --> 20:56.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VALI NASR: Well, I think that's
what they want. They want to
position themselves in

20:56.956 --> 21:00.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
there. They're in Syria.

21:00.926 --> 21:06.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They can provide underground
military operations, which the
U.S. and the Europeans don't
want

21:06.866 --> 21:14.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do right now, but also
getting a common language on
ISIS helps the Russians to
isolate

21:14.874 --> 21:21.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Turks and Saudi Arabia, which
still are insisting that the
problem is Assad, not ISIS.

21:21.480 --> 21:26.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of this is basically
positioning. And not much may
happen in the actual fighting,

21:26.418 --> 21:31.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but I think Putin finds a lot
more room to argue that I told
you so two years ago, this

21:31.924 --> 21:35.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is about terrorism, you wouldn't
believe me, it's not about
Assad, and if you want this

21:35.227 --> 21:38.497 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
thing to go away, we
should all focus on ISIS.

21:38.497 --> 21:43.335 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Evelyn Farkas, do
you agree that we have now moved
past the argument about

21:43.335 --> 21:49.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Assad and that, even though the
U.S. and France are on one side
and that Russia is on the

21:49.241 --> 21:52.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other side, that there has
to be some other pathway?

21:52.845 --> 21:57.016 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: I mean, I don't
think that we're aligned with
Russia yet. We really have

21:57.016 --> 21:59.919 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a disagreement, a fundamental
disagreement on Assad.

21:59.919 --> 22:06.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So until that bridge is -- until
that gap is bridged, which will
happen through diplomacy,

22:06.091 --> 22:12.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we won't see real change. We can
bomb ISIL, Da'esh, et cetera.
The Russians can bomb them.

22:12.998 --> 22:18.237 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it's still not going to
change the ultimate outcome.

22:18.237 --> 22:23.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the other thing is that,
right now, Russia wants a
resolution, because, right now,
they're

22:23.042 --> 22:25.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
probably at the peak of their
military engagement. I don't
know, quite frankly, how much
longer

22:25.444 --> 22:27.813 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they can sustain this.

22:27.813 --> 22:32.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It wasn't long ago
that we were talking about a
proxy war in Syria with the

22:32.351 --> 22:36.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. on one side, Russia on the
other, and the potential, I
don't know, for us shooting

22:36.121 --> 22:39.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
each other out of the sky and
the whole thing escalating. Has
that now gone away if we sit

22:39.325 --> 22:41.827 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
down at the same table?

22:41.827 --> 22:45.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALI NASR: No, I mean, on the
military arena, there are
certain things have to happen
about

22:45.464 --> 22:49.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
deconflicting and then getting
our at least targets aligned.

22:49.935 --> 22:55.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's in Vienna that we
might see the greatest amount of
movement. Namely, if the

22:55.374 --> 23:00.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Europeans and the Americans come
with an attitude of let us try
to find a compromise around

23:00.980 --> 23:07.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when will Assad go, how can we
bring a certain number of the
opposition forces into alignment

23:07.219 --> 23:12.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with the Syrian government to
create a united front to fight
ISIS, there might be movement

23:12.124 --> 23:13.626 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there.

23:13.626 --> 23:18.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think what Russia would like
is to move the U.S. and European
positions closer to

23:18.964 --> 23:23.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
themselves and break them off
from Turkey and Saudi Arabia,
which are still, if you

23:23.802 --> 23:27.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
want to call it, are holding to
the line that this is about
Assad, Assad must go before

23:27.573 --> 23:29.708 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we do anything else.

23:29.708 --> 23:32.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But at what price?
This is not the only agreement
that the U.S. and Russia

23:32.177 --> 23:33.112 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
have.

23:33.112 --> 23:34.980 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: Well, that's
what I was going to say.

23:34.980 --> 23:40.185 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think he's also trying to very
cleverly create a divide between
us and our European

23:40.185 --> 23:44.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allies. And that gets to a whole
context that's not even being
addressed here, which is what's

23:44.023 --> 23:47.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
happening in Europe, and
Ukraine-Russia, relations, et
cetera.

23:47.926 --> 23:53.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think that he has cleverly
-- he used the word treat them
as allies to his military

23:53.032 --> 23:57.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
folks when he was instructing
them about engaging with the
French navy. Treat them as
allies.

23:57.002 --> 24:00.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, the French actually have
allies. They have -- they're
part of a 28-member alliance

24:00.906 --> 24:05.210 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
called NATO. They're part of the
E.U. Russia is not their ally.

24:05.210 --> 24:11.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's a little bit of
an exuberant sort of
exaggeration to call the French
the

24:11.016 --> 24:14.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russian allies. But I think this
is Putin being very clever and
he's trying to create

24:14.853 --> 24:17.990 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some distance and pull off
the French towards himself.

24:17.990 --> 24:21.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And yet, next week,
we're going to see Francois
Hollande, who you say is not

24:21.327 --> 24:26.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an ally of Vladimir Putin and of
Russia, going to Moscow to meet,
also coming to the U.S.

24:26.465 --> 24:30.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to meet with President Obama,
trying to straddle that
difference.

24:30.803 --> 24:35.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VALI NASR: Well, I think there
is to be military and
intelligence cooperation
discussions.

24:35.107 --> 24:39.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But beyond that, I think the key
question is Europe -- is this,
is that you can't really

24:39.445 --> 24:43.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fight ISIS until you end this
war, so how are you going to end
this war? And I think

24:43.682 --> 24:47.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the proposal Putin is giving
everybody is that you're not
going to fight -- you're not

24:47.920 --> 24:51.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to get rid of Assad
anymore, because I'm protecting
him sitting here. And the only

24:51.590 --> 24:55.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
way this war is going to end is
if we arrive at a compromise.

24:55.728 --> 25:00.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think he's going to try to
persuade President Hollande to
agree to a formula, that then

25:00.632 --> 25:04.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Hollande when he meets
with President Obama will try to
sell it to Washington. And

25:04.703 --> 25:06.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if they're successful, then that
becomes the position in Vienna
around which there might

25:06.672 --> 25:08.407 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be a compromise.

25:08.407 --> 25:10.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Does that sound
reassuring to -- reassuring to
you?

25:10.876 --> 25:13.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: That sounds not
reassuring, not reassuring, but
it sounds reasonable.

25:13.779 --> 25:17.116 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It sounds like the course that
he would take. And I can't say
whether we would compromise

25:17.116 --> 25:17.383 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
or not.

25:17.383 --> 25:18.751 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

25:18.751 --> 25:21.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But is that worth
the paper it's written on, is
the question.

25:21.587 --> 25:24.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EVELYN FARKAS: Well, in terms of
the Russians, I think you have
to be really careful.

25:24.890 --> 25:29.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as I said, you have to
watch what they're hitting, what
they're not hitting and really

25:29.695 --> 25:32.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
test them, because, for a long
time, they have been talking
about cooperating with us,

25:32.765 --> 25:35.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but we have never really
seen it in action.

25:35.100 --> 25:42.641 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Evelyn Farkas, Vali
Nasr, thank you both very much.

25:42.641 --> 25:46.578 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
VALI NASR: Thank you.

25:46.578 --> 25:52.618 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

25:52.618 --> 25:58.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
ISIS seeks a new generation of
jihadists in Afghanistan.

25:58.290 --> 26:03.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, first, in the wake of the
Paris attacks, there is a
growing concern among Republican

26:03.762 --> 26:09.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
candidates, governors and
lawmakers about refugees from
Syria to the United States.

26:09.134 --> 26:12.271 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Political director Lisa
Desjardins reports.

26:12.271 --> 26:17.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: On the campaign
trail, Republican candidates
have seized on the refugee
issue.

26:17.609 --> 26:22.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ohio Governor John Kasich, who
initially said he might support
the resettlement of refugees

26:22.581 --> 26:26.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in his state, is now opposed. He
explained his thinking at a
national security speech

26:26.218 --> 26:28.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Washington today.

26:28.353 --> 26:31.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GOV. JOHN KASICH (R-OH),
Presidential Candidate: And once
we have a rational program and
we

26:31.223 --> 26:38.497 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can determine who it is that's
coming, then it's another story.
But at this point in time,

26:38.497 --> 26:42.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in light of what we're seeing in
the world, it's reasonable to
stop.

26:42.434 --> 26:45.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Last night at a
rally in Tennessee, it was
Donald Trump.

26:45.604 --> 26:48.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate: What I like is, build
a safe zone in Syria.

26:48.841 --> 26:53.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Build a big, beautiful safe
zone, and you have whatever it
is, so people can live and

26:53.378 --> 26:55.614 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they will be happier.

26:55.614 --> 27:00.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: The U.S. has
let in around 2,500 refugees
from Syria in the past four

27:00.886 --> 27:07.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years. In September, President
Obama unveiled a plan to welcome
10,000 more by next fall.

27:07.125 --> 27:11.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's just a fraction of the
migrants fleeing the region, and
officials say they face the

27:11.864 --> 27:16.268 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
toughest vetting of any
immigrants to the U.S.

27:16.268 --> 27:21.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Typically, that can mean two
years of processing or more. But
governors do not trust the
process,

27:21.607 --> 27:25.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and in the wake of the Paris
attacks, more than two dozen say
they now oppose Syrian

27:25.611 --> 27:29.781 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
refugees moving to their states.

27:29.781 --> 27:34.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still, governors technically
can't stop the federal
government from resettling
refugees

27:34.219 --> 27:39.191 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
within their borders. That means
all eyes are on Congress.

27:39.191 --> 27:43.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senate Majority Leader Mitch
McConnell today said he is
considering possible action.

27:43.262 --> 27:46.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. MITCH MCCONNELL (R-KY),
Majority Leader: What you're
hearing from all the governors

27:46.498 --> 27:53.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
around the country, saying
they're not interested in taking
refugees from Syria for the
foreseeable

27:53.739 --> 28:01.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
future, the -- at the very
least, it strikes me that we
need a pause or a moratorium.

28:01.813 --> 28:06.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Paul Ryan, the
new speaker of the House, pushed
his Republican Conference

28:06.051 --> 28:09.154 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to come up with a
plan, and soon.

28:09.154 --> 28:11.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REP. PAUL RYAN (R-WI), Speaker
of the House: We have assembled
a task force starting Saturday

28:11.290 --> 28:14.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to consider legislation
as quickly as possible.

28:14.760 --> 28:18.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: As Republicans
mustered to block refugees,
Attorney General Loretta Lynch

28:18.730 --> 28:22.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
defended the current system
today before a House panel.

28:22.301 --> 28:25.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LORETTA LYNCH, U.S. Attorney
General: There are challenges to
that process because of

28:25.971 --> 28:30.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the situation in Syria. But I
would note, however, that we do
have the benefit of having

28:30.242 --> 28:33.612 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that significant and robust
screening process in place.

28:33.612 --> 28:37.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: In a blog post
late today, the White House said
it continues to look

28:37.316 --> 28:41.386 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for ways to improve the
vetting of Syrian refugees.

28:41.386 --> 28:44.623 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
For the "PBS NewsHour,"
I'm Lisa Desjardins.

28:44.623 --> 28:49.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The next person to
occupy the White House will
likely be faced with the

28:49.027 --> 28:52.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
continuing fallout from
this week's Paris attacks.

28:52.998 --> 28:56.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we are joined by two of
the presidential candidates to
hear how they would handle
terror

28:56.268 --> 28:59.438 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
threats at home and abroad.

28:59.438 --> 29:02.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We begin with Democratic
candidate Senator Bernie Sanders
of Vermont.

29:02.074 --> 29:03.642 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome, Senator.

29:03.642 --> 29:05.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (VT-I),
Presidential Candidate: Good to
be with you.

29:05.544 --> 29:08.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: In the wake of the
Paris attacks, you have called
for what you describe as an

29:08.880 --> 29:12.951 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
international effort to
eliminate the stain of ISIS from
the world.

29:12.951 --> 29:15.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How would you do that?

29:15.420 --> 29:22.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. BERNIE SANDERS: The good
news, in the midst of all of
this tragedy, is that countries

29:22.194 --> 29:26.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all over the world, whether it
is France, whether it is Russia,
whether it is the Muslim

29:26.531 --> 29:33.105 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
countries in the Gulf region,
we now have a common interest.

29:33.105 --> 29:40.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is to come together to
destroy this barbaric
organization called ISIS. And
what

29:40.178 --> 29:45.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has got to happen -- and I don't
suggest this is easy, but we
have got to overcome a lot

29:45.417 --> 29:50.155 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the internal squabbling and
disagreements which now exist.

29:50.155 --> 29:56.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
God knows the United States,
correctly, has strong
differences of opinion with
Russia.

29:56.161 --> 30:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Iran and Saudi Arabia have very,
very strong differences of
opinion. But what leadership

30:02.100 --> 30:07.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
is about now is bringing
together all of these countries,
including the countries in the

30:07.839 --> 30:12.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Gulf region who have the most to
lose, and to say, you know what,
we're going to work

30:12.577 --> 30:18.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on a coordinated military
strategy and a political
strategy to destroy ISIS.

30:18.483 --> 30:22.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's what I have been saying
for a long time. And I believe
it is even truer today.

30:22.821 --> 30:27.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: In your opinion, has
the Obama administration done
enough to create a workable

30:27.325 --> 30:28.994 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
strategy?

30:28.994 --> 30:32.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. BERNIE SANDERS: This is
tough stuff, and I know it's
very easy to criticize the

30:32.030 --> 30:33.899 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
president.

30:33.899 --> 30:39.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think he has tried as hard
as he can. I think John Kerry
has been very effective

30:39.938 --> 30:45.043 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in trying to bring these
countries together. He got Saudi
Arabia and Iran to sit down in

30:45.043 --> 30:49.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a room. That is no small thing.
To get Turkey and the Kurds to
begin working together, no

30:49.081 --> 30:52.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
small thing, but that is
what has -- has to happen.

30:52.584 --> 30:57.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think we have got to do
more. I think the Obama
administration has made a very
good

30:57.055 --> 31:01.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
step forward, but we have got to
do more. I think we're seeing
some results in the G20

31:01.693 --> 31:05.297 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conferences that are taking
place and have taken place.

31:05.297 --> 31:10.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the bottom line is, we have
got to be in this together.
Russia lost over 200 people

31:10.969 --> 31:16.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in a flight. God knows we saw
what happened in Paris. We know
what's happened in the U.K.

31:16.475 --> 31:20.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are in this together. And
when we work together, not the
slightest doubt in my mind

31:20.746 --> 31:23.115 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that ISIS will be destroyed.

31:23.115 --> 31:27.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The other thing
that's happened since the Paris
attacks is what appears to

31:27.085 --> 31:33.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be a pretty strong, in this
country especially, anti-refugee
backlash, many, many governors

31:33.225 --> 31:35.927 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
saying, no, not in my state.

31:35.927 --> 31:36.928 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's your response to that?

31:36.928 --> 31:40.465 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SEN. BERNIE SANDERS: I disagree.

31:40.465 --> 31:48.173 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Look, when we talk about
terrorism, what it's really
about is the terrorists trying
to instill

31:48.173 --> 31:52.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fear and terror in ourselves.
And I'm hearing some people
talking, well, maybe we will
close

31:52.978 --> 31:58.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down mosques, maybe we won't let
Muslims into this country, maybe
we will turn our back

31:58.717 --> 32:03.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on hundreds of thousands of
people who have been
destroyed,whose lives have been
destroyed

32:03.088 --> 32:06.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by terrorism, who have had to
flee Syria, have to flee
Afghanistan.

32:06.858 --> 32:13.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, it goes without saying that
we need to have a very, very
strong screening process

32:13.632 --> 32:17.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to make sure that those people
who come into this country
deserve to be in this country,

32:17.536 --> 32:21.206 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that they are not terrorists.
I think that we can do that.

32:21.206 --> 32:27.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I will tell you something
else, that if we turn our backs
on those people, you know,

32:27.445 --> 32:34.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think in -- almost, in a way,
we will be -- we will be under
-- we will be destroying

32:34.452 --> 32:36.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
what this country is
supposed to be about.

32:36.788 --> 32:39.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Throughout our history, we have
